open_spaces_details.open_space_type: Allotments, community gardens and city farms

protected_spaces_details.description: Allotments, community gardens and city farms

application_type_full: Outline planning permission: Some matters reserved
description: Outline Planning Application for approval of means of access, with all other matters to be reserved (Environmental Impact Assessment Planning Application), for Phase 2 of the 15 year Regeneration of South Acton Estate, consisting of the demolition of Bollo, Maugham, Lawrence, Reade, Shaw, Hardy and Verne Courts, Blackmore and Kipling Towers, Working Men's Club, garages and storage units east side of Shaw Court; construction of 756 Residential Units, 2490m Retail (Class A1), 625m Office (Class A2 & B1) / Food & Drink (Class A3/A4/A5), 997m Live/Work Units, 100m General Industry (Class B2), 1775m Community / Leisure (Class D1 & D2) and a maximum of 617 car parking spaces. Some residential units provided on southern part of Recreation Ground and existing Allotments with relocation of allotments / open space (no net loss in open space).
decision_conditions: Approval of the details of siting, design, external appearance and landscaping (hereinafter called "the reserved matters") shall be obtained from the Local Planning Authority in writing before any development is commenced, or in respect of the scheme being phased, before any development is commenced in relation to that phase, or part thereof.   REASON:  The application is in outline form only and is not accompanied by full detailed plans. | Application for the approval of all the reserved matters shall be made to the local planning authority before the expiration of 3 years from the date of this permission.  REASON: In order to comply with the provisions of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 | The development hereby permitted shall be begun either before the expiration of five years of the date of this permission or before the expiration of two years from the date of approval of the last of the reserved matters to be approved, whichever is later.  REASON: In order to comply with the provisions of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990. | Details of the phasing of the entire development, including plans and floorspace figures shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority before commencement of construction of buildings, either individually or in groups, and the approved phasing scheme shall be implemented as approved.  REASON: To ensure the development proceeds in a balanced way including bringing forward appropriate and essential uses, such as shops, at the appropriate time to achieve the proper planning of the area in accordance with policy 1.1 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Plans and particulars of the reserved matters for each phase / part of the development referred to in condition 4 above, relating to siting, design, external appearance of buildings and landscaping of the site, shall be submitted in writing to the Local Planning Authority prior to the commencement of work on the relevant phase, and the plans and particulars shall be carried out only as approved.  REASON: To ensure that no development of the various phases / parts of the development commences until reserved matters for each phase / part of the total development are approved. This condition reflects the provisions of Section 92 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 and Article 4 of the Town and Country Planning (General Development Procedure) Order 1995. | Detailed drawings, including a phased programme, showing all highway improvements and new infrastructure within the appropriate sections of the new roads, and proposed new pedestrian & cycle routes shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of the development. The approved scheme shall be implemented in accordance with a programme to be agreed in writing by the local planning authority and be retained for the life of the development.  REASON: To ensure the development is properly designed and implemented in the interests of highway safety for pedestrians, cyclists and vehicles. In accordance with policies 1.9 and 9.1 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Detailed Drawings Prior to commencement of construction of each phase / part of the total development hereby approved, the following details and detailed drawings shall be submitted to and be approved in writing by the local planning authority:  i)  The siting of all buildings and ancillary structures relative to the surrounding development, approved or future phases/parts of the total development; ii)  The traffic arrangements within the site, including means of ingress and egress, visibility splays and the phasing of any construction work; iii)  The means of construction and surfacing of all roads, drives, parking areas and footpaths; iv)  The finished levels of the development in relation to the levels of the surrounding area and the ordnance datum;  vi)  Full plans, elevations and sections of all buildings, screen walls and structures to an appropriate scale, incorporating details of all materials to be used for external surfaces including samples of all such materials; vii)  The treatment of all site boundaries for each phase/part of the development incorporating full details of heights and materials; viii)  The facilities to be provided for the storage of refuse and waste materials awaiting disposal, including recycling facilities, and full plans and elevations of structures or screening shall be shown; ix)  Details of external lighting; x)  Details of bicycle and pedestrian routes;  xi)  Details of acoustic treatment and ventilation to all buildings; xii)  Details of access for people with disabilities; xiii)  Details of measures to improve biodiversity.  Implementation of the said phase/part of the development shall be carried out only in accordance with the details approved by the Local Planning Authority and shall be retained as such for the lifetime of the development.  REASON:  In order to ensure the development achieves a quality external appearance and is environmentally sound and compatible with surrounding development / land uses, in accordance with policies 1.1,1.4, 1.9, 2.1, 2.10, 4.1, 4.5, 4.11, 4.12, 5.5 and 9.1of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | The access and traffic arrangements approved in respect of each phase/part of the development, in compliance with condition (7), shall be provided before that phase/part of the development is occupied or first brought into use.  Thereafter those access and traffic arrangements shall be retained.  REASON: To ensure that adequate access arrangements exist to serve the development. In accordance with policy 9.1of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Details of car parking provision and pedestrian access in accordance with the standards adopted by the Local Planning Authority shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority before any works commence on site.  Such provision to be brought into use prior to the first occupation of the relevant phase/ part of the development permitted and retained permanently.  REASON: To ensure that there is adequate provision for car parking and pedestrians within the site. In accordance with policy 9.1of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Details of the turning/loading/unloading facilities in respect of each phase/part of the development, shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to commencement of construction of each phase/part of the development. Such details shall accord with the current standards of the Local Planning Authority and shall be provided before that phase/part of the development is occupied or first brought into use. Thereafter they shall be retained for such purpose.  REASON: To ensure that adequate facilities are provided and retained to service the development without creating conditions prejudicial to the free flow and safety of traffic on the adjacent highway network. . In accordance with policy 9.1of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | No development shall take place until full details of both hard and soft landscape works, for all open areas not covered by buildings or roads, paying particular attention to the retention and replacement of trees and including a phased programme of works, have been submitted to and approved in writing by the local  planning authority and these works shall be carried out as approved prior to the occupation of any part of the development or in accordance with the programme agreed by the local planning authority.  Any trees or other plants, which die or are removed within the first five years following the implementation of the landscaping scheme, shall be replaced during the next planting season.  REASON: To ensure that the development is landscaped in the interests of the visual character and appearance of the area. In accordance with policy 4.5 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | The entire root system of trees to be retained, as shown on the approved drawings, indicated by the spread of their branches, shall be protected by stout exclusion fencing until completion of the development (to BS5837 requirements).  REASON:  To prevent damage to the trees in the interest of the visual character and appearance of the area, in accordance with policies 4.2 and 4.5 of the Council's adopted UDP, "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | The area beneath the spread of the branches of the trees to be retained as shown on the approved drawings shall not be used for the storage of building materials, plant, machinery or other items, or for vehicular access or for the burning of materials of any kind.  REASON:  To prevent damage to the trees in the interest of the visual character and appearance of the area, in accordance with policy 4.5 of the Council's adopted UDP, "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Permanent planting pits shall be installed for street trees to be planted.  REASON: To avoid conflict with underground services. In accordance with policy 4.5 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Details of the layout of play areas for the children of residents and visitors shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority prior to the construction of the development or the particular phase of the development being commenced. Such play areas as may be approved shall be provided prior to the first occupation of the development or that particular phase of the development and shall be retained for the life of the development.  REASON: To ensure the satisfactory development and provision of play facilities. In accordance with policies 4.5 and 8.6 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Diagrams demonstrating the amount of sunlight entering the courtyards of the new buildings at appropriate times shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority before commencement of any development in relation to each phase/part of the development hereby approved.   REASON: To enable full assessment and to satisfy the local planning authority that a satisfactory standard of amenity can be achieved within these spaces. In accordance with policy 4.1 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | No development shall take place until the applicant has secured the implementation of a programme of archaeological work in accordance with a written scheme for investigation which has been submitted by the applicant and approved by the Local Planning Authority. The archaeological works shall be carried out by a suitably qualified investigating body acceptable to the Local Planning Authority.  REASON: To safeguard areas of potential archaeological interest in accordance with policy 4.9 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Details of a scheme of security measures, for public and private areas of the development, shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority prior to the commencement of work on each phase or part of the development. The approved scheme shall be implemented prior to completion and occupation of each phase/part of the development and thereafter be permanently retained.  REASON: To promote community safety in accordance with policy 4.1 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | A demolition and construction strategy shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority prior to commencement of any development in relation to any phase/part of the development hereby approved and thereafter implemented as approved. Such strategy shall address the following matters:  - Limiting hours of noise nuisance - Keeping nearby accesses free from obstruction and segregating construction and general traffic - No burning of waste on site - The suppression of dust - The location and means of enclosure of sites for the storage of plant, materials and construction of staff accommodation - Means of securely enclosing construction sites - Any temporary road measures  REASON: To ensure that any impacts on residential amenity and general disruption are minimised during the construction process related to the total development hereby approved. In accordance with policies 2.6, 4.1 and 9.9 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | The development hereby permitted shall not exceed an overall density of 452 habitable rooms per hectare.  REASON: To ensure that the site is not overdeveloped, in the interests of the visual character of the area and the living conditions of residents and neighbouring occupiers. In accordance with policies 4.1 and 5.1 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Before any parts of the development is commenced, a Flood Risk Assessment shall be carried out and details of a scheme for the disposal of surface water and sewage, in respect of each phase/part of the development, shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority.  All works, which form part of this scheme, shall be carried out before that phase/part of the development is first occupied or brought into use.  REASON: To ensure that the proposed drainage of the development is in accordance with the standards and that the development does not pollute the water environment, or give rise to an increased risk of flooding, nor to an overloading of the sewage system in the locality. In accordance with policy 2.5 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | The submission of any application for Reserved Matters approval must be accompanied by a detailed Design Code. This Design Code must be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority at the same time as the first application for approval of Reserved Matters, made under this Outline Permission. The detail of the development, which is to be designed under the Outline Permission hereby granted, and any subsequent application for approval of Reserved Matters made under this Outline Permission must be constructed in accordance with the approved Design Code documentation.  REASON: In the interests of the proper planning of the area in accordance with policies 1.4 and  4.1 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Before any works commence on site, details of a scheme to provide parking for cyclists in accordance with adopted standards shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority, and such details as approved shall be implemented and brought into use prior to first occupation, and retained permanently.  REASON: To provide adequate facilities for cyclists. In accordance with policy 9.6 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Details of a 'Green Building Scheme' to embrace all buildings within the development shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority before construction of the buildings (individually or in groups) and the approved scheme shall thereafter be implemented as approved.  REASON: In the interests of energy efficiency and to secure as sustainable development as possible. In accordance with policies 2.1 and 2.9 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Details of numbers and location of parking spaces to be provided for the 'City Car Club' shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning prior to the commencement of the development. Such parking provision as is approved shall be provided and be operational before any of the dwellings it relates to are first occupied and shall thereafter be permanently retained.  REASON: To ensure that appropriate car parking facilities are available so that the City Car Club is able to function and that all residents have reasonable access to a car in the interests of accessibility to off site facilities and services. In accordance with policies 9.1 and 9.8 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | The Urban Design Framework (UDF) accompanying this outline application shall be reviewed at each stage of the development and any consequent revisions shall be submitted to the local planing authority for approval. Development shall be carried out in accordance with the UDF.  REASON: To ensure that the overall development is carried out according to the principles agreed by the local planning authority in the interest of the proper planning of the area. In accordance with policy 4.1 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | The rating noise level emitted from the proposed development, as assessed under BS4142: 1997, shall be lower than the existing background noise by at least 5 dBA at 3.5m from the nearest ground floor sensitive facade and 1 m from the nearest first floor or higher.  REASON: In the interests of the living conditions of neighbours, in accordance with policy 4.11 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Parts of the development will be affected by noise from traffic, rail and industrial sources at a level, which falls into Category B or C noise exposure.  Prior to the commencement of the development, details shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority, for mitigation works to protect sensitive rooms, gardens and balconies from external noise and vibration, [and sensitive rooms from internal building services noise].  The criteria to be met and the assessment method shall be that specified at Document 5.3 "Guidance for developers".  The details shall also include alternative means of ventilation for noise sensitive rooms, meeting the said criteria. The works, as approved, shall be completed before first occupation and thereafter be permanently retained.  REASON: In the interest of the living conditions of future occupiers in accordance with policy 4.11 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Details shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority, before the development is commenced, for isolation of the foundations of all new dwelling blocks from railway vibration. No timber frame construction or other lightweight construction shall be used unless it has first been satisfactorily demonstrated to the local planning authority that such structures can achieve an appropriate level of protection against railway vibration. The development shall be constructed only in accordance with such measures as may be approved.  REASON: In order to prevent the transmission of nuisance vibrations into dwellings. In accordance with policy 4.11 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Details of times of operation of food take away premises and community and leisure facilities with or without amplified music shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to commencement of the use  REASON: In the interests of neighbouring amenity in accordance with policies 4.11 and 7.6 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Details shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority before the development is commenced, for the installation and operation of the best practicable odour abatement equipment and also for the height of any exhaust stack for restaurants, hot food take-aways and any other premises emitting odour. Such details as may be approved shall be implemented before the use first commences and shall be retained for the life of the use.  REASON: In the interests of neighbouring amenity in accordance with policy 4.2 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Details, to demonstrate that commercial plant and building services plant inside the commercial part(s) of the premises, which is audible inside dwellings within the same building, will be designed to satisfy an acoustic standard not exceeding LFNR 20 Leq,5min (2300 - 0700hrs) (Bedrooms) and LFNR 25 Leq,1hr (0700 -2300hrs) (Living Rooms), shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning.  Such details as may be approved shall be implemented before first commencement of the use and be permanently maintained.  REASON: In the interests of neighbouring amenity in accordance with policy 4.2 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Details shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority before the development is first commenced, for a suitable sound limiting device to control the output from the amplification system to a maximum noise level agreed with the local planning authority.  The limiter device shall also be connected to all external doors so that the power to the amplifiers will be cut if a door is opened, other than for means of escape from fire. Such details as are approved shall be installed before the use first commences and shall be permanently retained.  REASON: In the interests of neighbouring amenity in accordance with policy 4.11of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Details shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority before any development is commenced, for the composite sound reduction index, Rw, of the building envelope of community/leisure uses with amplified music, with windows and doors closed and other means of ventilation provided, to demonstrate that the insulation is sufficient to prevent noise disturbance.  The approved insulation shall be implemented before the development is commenced and retained permanently thereafter.  REASON: In the interests of neighbouring amenity in accordance with policy 4.11of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Details shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority before the development of community and leisure uses with amplified music is commenced, for a suitable mechanical ventilation system, to ensure doors and windows are kept closed during hot weather and externally sited ventilation plant associated with this system will be silenced to a standard not exceeding NR 35 Leq,5min (2300 - 0700hrs), measured or calculated at 1m from the nearest facade of the nearest affected noise sensitive premises. Such details as may be approved shall be installed before the first use of the premises and shall be permanently maintained.  REASON: In the interests of neighbouring amenity in accordance with policy 4.11of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Prior to the commencement of any works on site, a contaminated land investigation shall be carried out, using sampling points and methods agreed with the Local Planning Authority and subsequently a risk assessment shall be prepared, following the CLEA guidance.  A scheme shall then be submitted for approval to describe the proposed methods of removal, neutralising or sealing of any contamination found, and for the remedial works to be implemented before any other works commence. Any scheme for mitigation which may be approved shall be carried out as approved before the development is carried out.  REASON: In the interests of ensuring a safe environment in accordance with policy 2.7 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Notwithstanding any indication as to the number of car parking spaces to be provided within the development hereby approved, the total parking provision within the development shall not exceed 48% (a ratio of parking spaces to residential units of 0.48:1). This figure shall include a provision of 10% (a ratio of 1:10) provided to disability standard for all new residential units.  REASON: To ensure an appropriate and sustainable level of car parking provision in accordance with policies 2.1 and 9.8 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Notwithstanding the provisions of Classes A, B, C, D, E and F of Part 1 of Schedule 2 to the Town and Country Planning (General Permitted Development) Order 1995,  No additions or extensions to any dwellinghouses which may subsequently be approved, including to their roofs, or alterations to the shape of any roofs of the dwellinghouses, or the erection or construction of any porch outside any external door of the dwellinghouses, or the provision within the curtilage of the dwellinghouses of any buildings or enclosures, or any hardstandings to the front of any dwellinghouses shall be carried out without the prior permission of the Local Planning Authority, obtained through the submission of a planning application.   REASON:  To prevent the overdevelopment of the site and to safeguard the living conditions of adjoining properties and visual appearance of the building. In accordance with policy 4.1 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | The roof space of any buildings which may subsequently be approved and provided shall not be converted into additional living accommodation without the prior permission of the local planning authority obtained through the submission of a planning application.  REASON: In order to prevent overdevelopment and increased density harmful to the living conditions of occupiers of the area. In accordance with policy 4.1of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Any flat roofs of any buildings or parts of buildings which may subsequently be approved and provided shall not be used to form a balcony, roof garden or similar amenity area, without the prior permission in writing of the local planning authority obtained through the submission of a planning application.  REASON: In order to protect the privacy, and other amenity, of neighbouring occupiers. In accordance with policy 4.1 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Any domestic garages, including in any of the buildings which may subsequently be approved and provided for the storage of motor vehicles, with the exception of any Live/Work units which may subsequently be approved in detail, shall only be used for domestic purposes and not for any industrial, commercial or business use, and no domestic garage in association with any residential accommodation shall be used to provide living accommodation which is separate and not incidental to that accommodation.  REASON: in the interest of neighbouring amenity and the free flow of vehicular and pedestrian traffic. In accordance with policies 4.1, 4.11 and 9.9 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Notwithstanding any indication given in this application or in documentation accompanying this planning application, the retail uses within the Neighbourhood Square hereby permitted shall be subject to the following restrictions:  (1)  the maximum gross floor area of any food convenience store shall be no more   than 1500 sq m. (2)  the maximum total floor area of any unit or units retailing non-food goods (excluding the food convenience store) shall be no more than 250 sq m. (3)  the maximum floor area in Use Class A1 retail shall not exceed 1750 sq m gross.  REASON: In the interests of ensuring the continuing viability of Acton Town Centre in accordance with policies 7.1 and 7.2 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Notwithstanding any indication given within the submitted plans, the submission of any application for approval of Reserved Matters in relation to residential uses must incorporate a design which ensures that at least 10% of the total units of each type of residential tenure is to a standard which equates with the requirements for properties to be accessible to those who utilise wheelchairs.  The approved matters shall be implemented prior to first occupation of the units.  REASON: In the interests of ensuring inclusive development in accordance with policy 4.3 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | All residential units hereby approved shall be constructed to Lifetime Homes Standards or the equivalent RSL standard, unless otherwise agreed by the Local Planning Authority, details of which shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to commencement of works.  The approved details shall be implemented prior to first occupation.  REASON: To ensure access for all for future occupiers in accordance with Policy 5.3 of the adopted UDP 2004. | The submission of any Reserved Matters application must include a mix of housing types that accords with approved document 5127/PL/1310 Rev D entitled Residential Accommodation Schedule, subject to further consideration, as part of the design process leading to the submission of Reserved Matters, of the need for a greater number of larger units (i.e. units with 3 + bedrooms). A specific report upon this issue shall be submitted as part of the first application for approval of Reserved Matters that is submitted in accordance with the Outline Permission hereby granted. The development hereby approved, and any approval of Reserved Matters made under this Outline Permission must be constructed in accordance with the approved documentation unless otherwise agreed in writing with the local planning authority, in which case any variation to this mix must accord with the content of the adopted UDP and the London Plan.  REASON: To ensure an appropriate range of dwelling types in accordance with policy 5.4 of the Council's Adopted UDP "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Notwithstanding the details shown on the approved plan, Ref. 5127/PL/1156 Rev E, full details of the highway layout and associated space around this highway shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority, at the Reserved Matters stage, in consultation with the Greater London Authority, prior to the commencement of any development upon the site. The use of this highway, including by public transport, cycle and private car (including any changes in permitted use at different times of day/day of the week) shall be controlled in accordance with a detailed scheme to be submitted as part of any Reserved Matters application that is submitted in accordance with the outline permission hereby granted.  REASON: To ensure that future opportunities for improving the permeability of the site and its connectivity with the surrounding area can be explored in the light of up to date information available at that time. In accordance with policies 4.1 and 9.1of the Council's Adopted UDP, "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Notwithstanding the details shown on the approved plan, Ref. 5127/PL/1156 Rev E, full details of the highway layout and its connectivity to existing highway around but outside the application site shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority, at the Reserved Matters stage, in consultation with the Greater London Authority, prior to the commencement of any development upon the site. The use of this highway, including by public transport, cycle and private car (including any changes in permitted use at different times of day/day of the week) shall be controlled in accordance with a detailed scheme to be submitted as part of any Reserved Matters application that is submitted in accordance with the outline permission hereby granted.  REASON: To ensure that future opportunities for improving the permeability of the site and its connectivity with the surrounding area can be explored in the light of up to date information available at that time. In accordance with policies 4.1 and 9.1of the Council's Adopted UDP, "Plan for the Environment" 2004. | Notwithstanding the information on the submitted building height parameter plan, this permission does not grant planning permission for all building blocks to reach the maximum heights illustrated on plan no. 5127/PL/1175 or the approved Planning Parameters Schedule 5127/PL/1310 rev D. Prior to submission of Reserved Matters, a definitive building height parameter plan shall be submitted to the local planning authority for approval, in consultation with the Greater London Authority and the development shall be carried out in strict accordance with such approval.  REASON: To ensure that the bulk and massing of the blocks relate satisfactorily to each other and to neighbouring developments so as to ensure that the final plan accords with the Principles for Compact City, described in policy 4B.1 of the 2004 London Plan and with policy 4.1 of Ealing's adopted Unitary Development Plan. | A site-wide energy strategy shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority, at the Reserved Matters stage, in consultation with the Greater London Authority, prior to the commencement of any development upon the site.
